{"questionId":"21595","questionHtml":"<p>A capacitor is charged with a constant current <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>I</mi></math>. The graph shows the variation of potential&nbsp;difference <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>V</mi></math> across the capacitor with time <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>t</mi></math>. The gradient of the graph is <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>G</mi></math>. What is the&nbsp;capacitance of the capacitor?</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\">&nbsp;<img src=\"__IMG__/9a302c256a1e42d9d8cda5332ece89a7c3ce7270.png\"></p>\n<p>A.&nbsp;&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mi>I</mi><mi>G</mi></mfrac></math></p>\n<p>B.&nbsp;&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mi>G</mi><mi>I</mi></mfrac></math></p>\n<p>C.&nbsp;&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>G</mi><mo>×</mo><mi>I</mi></math></p>\n<p>D.&nbsp;&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mrow><mi>G</mi><mo>×</mo><mi>I</mi></mrow></mfrac></math></p>","markschemeHtml":"<p>A</p>","meta":{"questionId":"21595","referenceCode":"21M.1.HL.TZ2.36","subjectId":"46-dp-physics-last-assessment-2024","title":"A capacitor is charged with a constant current I. The graph shows the variation of potential difference V across the capacitor with time t. The gradient of the graph is G. What is ","paper":"1","level":"HL","questionNumber":"36","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 1]","breadcrumbLabels":["Additional higher level (AHL)","Additional higher level (AHL)","Topic 11: Electromagnetic induction","11.3 – Capacitance","Additional higher level (AHL)","Topic 11: Electromagnetic induction"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}